		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2023"></a><br><code>sle2023/paper12</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2023</a> paper:</span><br><i>Cascade: A Meta-language for Change, Cause and Effect</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/RiemervanRozen.html">Riemer van Rozen</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3623476.3623515">10.1145/3623476.3623515</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagM">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> Cascade is presented as a meta-language for expressing change, cause-and-effect, and interpreter behavior for DSLs.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> The meta-language is explicitly aimed at creating and retrofitting domain-specific languages with live-programming features.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4b.html"><span class="tagL">T4B: Horizontal Transformation</span></a><ul><li> The approach relies on (bi-directional) model transformations and migrations to represent and propagate change.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagL">T4D: Interpretation</span></a><ul><li> The accompanying runtime (Delta) executes transformations and maintains histories during program execution.
</li></ul></li></ul>
